Climate Impact on Agricultural Productivity

Project Report for STAT 303-1 Fall 2025

Author

Sophia Perez

Published

December 9, 2025

Abstract

This study integrates four analytical approaches to assess how climate change influences crop yields and broader economic outcomes. First, these analytical questions allow for the study of how climate and agriculture vary over time and on a regional level. Across analyses, temperature patterns and extreme weather events consistently emerged as the primary drivers of agricultural performance. While global temperature trends showed no strong temporal patterns, regional analyses revealed substantial geographic variation, indicating that climate impacts are more meaningfully interpreted at the regional scale. Furthermore, the analysis questions worked to answer how well climate change variables correlated with crop yield and how they affect the economy. A key global finding shows that crop yields peak within an average temperature range of 10–20°C. Activity of Very High extreme weather event levels has also increased in recent years, is most frequent in the United States, and coincides with relatively higher U.S. crop yields under severe conditions. Economic impact also showed a strong positive linear relationship with crop yield. These findings together highlight the need for region-specific climate policies and agricultural investments that enhance crop and soil resilience against climate change events, which can overall have an impact on economic welfare.

We were also able to see similar production processes for sugarcane and cacao. 2) Problem Statements

  1. What are overall trends and patterns in crop yield, climate variables, and agricultural factors over the years?
    • Before beginning a full analysis of the dataset, it is important to first visualize how different variables act across the given set of years (1990-2024). This facilitates the identification of patterns and an understanding of long-term trends. More specifically, this question will look at how the following variables change over time: crop yield, average temperature, total precipitation, CO2 emissions, extreme weather events, and soil health index.
  2. What regions are experiencing the greatest changes in these 3 categories?
    • From the first question, the key variable for each category (crop yield, climate variables, and agricultural factors) will be chosen to analyze from a geographical perspective. This will help identify regions experiencing the most significant changes over time to highlight areas that may be more vulnerable or resilient to certain factors. Three key tasks will be used to answer this question. First, temperature will be plotted across each region in each country to visually map how distinct the climate differences are within each country. Second, the top ten regions with the greatest crop yield and soil health index changes will be found and visualized. Third, extreme weather events by country will be visualized on a heatmap.
  3. How do climate change factors correlate with crop yield?
    • For this question, we are attempting to see if the climate influences crop yield. Using the information found in the previous 2 questions, different methods of visualizations will be used to determine correlation, including pairplots, heatmaps, subplots, and boxplots.
  4. How do climate change and agricultural practices collectively influence the economic impact of crop production globally?
    • For the final question, I will analyze the most significant variables from the previous 3 questions in relation to economic impact. Specifically, barplots and regression plots will be used to show how economic impact changes in different scenarios. Adaptation strategies will also be analyzed in this question to determine if certain adaptation strategies have a higher economic impact. This question will tie the climate and agricultural aspects of this report to the societal aspects.

5) Data Cleaning

A brief scan of the entire dataset was conducted before cleaning it specifically for each question. As a result, it was determined that there were no missing or NaN values in any of the 15 variables, and outliers were only present in the Economic_Impact_Million_USD variable. This information was used in considering data cleaning methods and techniques to address the following questions.

a) Cleaning - Question 1

What are the overall trends and patterns in crop yield, climate variables, and agricultural factors over the years?

To answer this question, all variables excluding Country, Region, Adaptation_Strategies, and Economic_Impact will need to be cleaned. The excluded variables are not useful for answering this question, as we are measuring overall environmental and agriculture trends across the years between 1990-2024, not societal impact. As observed earlier, there are no missing values in any of the necessary variables, so imputation is not required. Furthermore, there are no outliers in any of these variables, so there is no need for adjustment in the values used. The only categorical variable used in this question is Crop Type. There are 10 different categories in this variable: Corn, Wheat, Coffee, Sugarcane, Fruits, Rice, Barley, Vegetables, Soybeans, and Cotton. This variable will be used later on in the analysis by grouping trends across the different crop types. However, two tasks were accomplished to ensure the data was ready for analysis. First, Extreme_Weather_Events and Soil_Health_Index were binned to more easily visualize trends, and second, inconsistencies in the numeric variables were checked.

Binning Extreme_Weather_Events

In the original data, the Extreme_Weather_Events variable indicates the number of modeled extreme weather occurrences per year. It is easier to see patterns within this variable and make visualizations more readable if the number of events is binned into 4 categories: Low, Medium, High, and Very High. Very High was included as a label due to two main factors: skewedness and how the data was binned. First, upon using a histogram visualization, this variable was determined to be heavily skewed left, with a high frequency of observations landing in the 9-10 range of the number of events. This is problematic because if equal-width bins are used, there may be different numbers of observations in each bin and make the analysis misleading. This brings us to our second point. The variable was binned into bins of equal size, not equal widths, and labeled with categories mentioned above. This avoids any irregularities due to skewedness and provides us with more insight into which observations in the data have Very High levels of extreme weather events. This binned variable was saved into a new copy of the original dataset.

Binning Soil_Health_Index

While the original dataset does not specify the type of soil test used to identify the soil health index, the Cornell Soil Health Test is a common test to use and utilizes the same scale. According to the Cornell Soil Health Test, ratings between 0-60 indicate limited levels of functioning. Ratings between 60-80 indicate soil functioning at a non-limiting level. Ratings above 80 indicate very high functioning levels [1]. Therefore, it is natural to bin the soil health index in the dataset since there is potential for analytical inconsistencies. The Soil_Health_Index variable was binned into the 3 previously defined categories: 0-59, indicating poor/fair; 60-79, indicating good; and 80-100, indicating excellent soil health. Since these ranges were scientifically defined, the bins are neither of equal size nor of equal width; they are custom.

Checking for Inconsistencies

Because multiple numeric variables are being used for this question, all of the data must be entered correctly. For example, the only variable that should have any negative values is Average_Temperature_C. This is proven to be accurate when 1185 observations had a negative value in that variable. All other variables had 0 negative values. Furthermore, percentages can’t be outside the range of 0-100%. The variable that uses a percentage is Irrigation_Access_%, which ranges from 10.01% to 99.99%. In finding the ranges of the data, it is also important to note that while the soil health index has a 0-100 range scale, this data only ranges from 30-100. All other variables used for this question were also visually checked for inconsistencies, and the values have been determined to be reasonable for use.

b) Cleaning - Question 2

What regions are experiencing the greatest changes in the 3 categories from Question 1?

As mentioned previously, there are no missing values in any of the variables used for this question, nor are the outliers. The categories excluded for this question are: Pesticide_Use, Fertilizer_Use, Adaptation_Strategies, and Economic_Impact because they are irrelevant to answering the question.

For this question, yearly trends discovered in question 1 will now be compared across different regions within countries. Upon analyzing the Country variable in the data, there are only 10 countries total: India, China, France, Canada, USA, Argentina, Australia, Nigeria, Russia, and Brazil. This only puts 1-2 countries in each global region; therefore, it can be misleading to compare regional trends on a global level. However, the Region variable contains many sub-national regions across the dataset, giving a more detailed breakdown than the country-level variable. This makes it more effective to compare trends within countries, especially given their large land areas and significant climate variability.

Given this information, there are two primary tasks for the cleaning of the data at this level. The first task is ensuring country names are consistent and regions are specific to the country they represent. The second task is checking for equal time coverage across countries. For example, if Brazil has data spanning the years 1990-2024, but Argentina only has the years 2000-2025, there may be inconsistencies in the analysis.

Cleaning the Country and Region Variables

In looking at all of the unique strings within the Country variable, it was determined that all strings represented a unique country in the world. However, in looking at the unique strings within the Region variable, the strings are ambiguous as to which country they pertain to. For example, North is a region, but it pertains to both North Brazil and North China. To remedy this, each region was paired with its country by putting each country in parentheses after the region that it corresponds to. This removes any ambiguities in the Region variable.

Checking for Equal Time Coverage Across Countries

As mentioned previously, it is important to check the span of years for each country to avoid a misleading analysis. Since the regions are sub-national for each country, the range of the years within each region was calculated; each region had a range of 34 years. Since the data spans from 1990-2024, 34 years is the maximum range a region can have. Therefore, it was determined that every region contains the full range of years, making the regional comparisons valid and consistent.

c) Cleaning - Question 3

How do climate change factors correlate with crop yield?

For this question, the variables that will be used are Crop_Type, Crop_Yield, and the climate variables from question 1: Average_Temperature_C, Total_Precipitation_mm, CO2_Emmissions_MT, and Extreme_Weather_Events. Since these variables were previously cleaned in previous questions, there is not much cleaning to do for question 3. Pesticide_Use and Fertilizer_Use will also be used to see if there is any correlation with crop yield. These variables have been checked for missing values, outliers, and inconsistencies with the other previously cleaned variables through the general cleaning of the entire dataset.

As a reminder, there are also no missing values in any of the variables, and there are no outliers in the variables being used for this question.

One-Hot Encoding Crop_Type

For the Crop_Type variable, there are 10 different crop types. However, in future studies, we may want to see how the relationship between climate variables and crop yield differs by crop type, so it is necessary to one-hot-encode. One-hot encoding is the process of creating numeric dummy variables for nominal categorical variables. “Crop_Type is a nominal variable because there is no inherent order in its categories (ex. Wheat, Coffee, Rice, Fruits). Once the variable is OHE, it can now be used to do future analysis studies. While the dummy variables may not be used for this study, they can be helpful for future studies on machine learning models or regression analysis.

d) Cleaning - Question 4

How do climate change and agricultural practices collectively influence economic impact from crop production globally?

For this question, we will be using the collective analysis from the previous three questions to determine if they have an influence on Economic_Impact_Million_USD and what that influence is. We can even go further to study how Adaptation_Strategies adjust in response to certain economic changes or even over the years.

To reiterate once more, there are also no missing values in any of the variables, so imputation is not necessary. We will collectively use all variables provided to answer this question except: Pesticide_Use, Fertilizer_Use. Based on previous cleaning, the only variables that need to be cleaned here are: Economic_Impact_Million_USD and Adaptation_Strategies.

Cleaning Economic_Impact_Million_USD

As identified in the general analysis of the dataset, this variable contains 177 outliers based on Tukey’s Fences, calculated using the IQR and relevant percentiles. All of these outliers are high outliers, meaning they fall above the upper fence. To determine whether these values should be removed, their plausibility was assessed. Since economic impact is expected to increase with crop yield, extremely high economic values would only be reasonable if they are associated with relatively high crop yields. To evaluate this, all outlier observations were isolated into a separate sub-dataset. Among these outliers, the lowest crop yield was 3.56, whereas the average crop yield across the entire dataset is 2.24. This indicates that the outliers correspond to crop yields that are not unusually low, and are in fact above the overall average. Therefore, the high economic impact values appear plausible and can be retained in the analysis, as no inconsistencies were found between the economic values and their associated crop yields.

Cleaning Adaptation_Strategies

The main thing to check for in this variable is if the categories listed are simple and concise enough to be understood. There are 5 unique categories in this variable: Water Management, Crop Rotation, No Adaptation, Organic Farming, and Drought-resistant Crops. All five of these categories are clear, distinct, and understandable to the average reader, so no further cleaning is needed.

Part 2: Regions with Greatest Changes in Crop Yield, Extreme Weather Events, and Soil Health Index

For this part of the analysis, we now want to look at which regions had the greatest changes in the three chosen variables. This helps us identify where the most significant shifts have occurred and which areas may need future study. To keep things simple, I measure the net change between 1990 and 2024. This allows me to clearly identify which regions experienced true long-term shifts, which is more appropriate given that these variable types evolve gradually rather than fluctuating meaningfully from year to year. Furthermore, we are looking for the greatest absolute difference because climate change can cause both increases and decreases that have major consequences, and understanding the size of these shifts matters more than their direction.

After grouping by the Country and Region, I applied a function that would subtract the value of the variable from the first year from the first year. Then the magnitude of this value was used to identify where the biggest change occurred. For each variable, the region-country pairs were then sorted, and the top 10 regions that have exhibited the greatest change for each variable were selected.

These steps were only taken for the Crop_Yield variables and Soil_Health_Index variables because the Extreme_Weather_Events variable have discrete values from 0-10, so a quantifiable difference can’t be measured in the same way as the other two variables.

Finally, we examine the variable Extreme_Weather_Events to identify the regions with the greatest change. Because these events are already binned, we want to see which countries have the highest counts of Very High Levels because this indicates which regions are experiencing the most extreme weather, which is particularly relevant for assessing climate risk and vulnerability. It may also be interesting to see how each level of extreme weather events varies per country. Therefore, a heatmap can display countries on the y-axis and extreme weather event levels on the x-axis. For simplicity, we analyze data at the country level rather than by region, since there are 40 regions and including them would make the heatmap too noisy without revealing clear patterns.

For this, a pivot table was created with the Country as the index, Extreme_Weather_Events as the columns, and the aggregation by size. The heatmap was then generated using this data.

Answer to the Question

This question aimed to identify which regions/countries are most affected by changes in agricultural and climate variables. For Crop Yield and Soil Health index, this meant looking at net change over the set of years. For Extreme Weather Events, this meant looking at which countries currently experience the highest levels at each category.

The region with the greatest change in Crop Yield over time was Northeast Brazil, with a magnitude of 2.691. The region with the greatest change in Soil Health Index over time was South Brazil, with a magnitude of 54.30. The primary countries present in the top 10 across both variables are Brazil, appearing 4 times; Argentina, appearing 6 times; and Russia, appearing 4 times. These regions and countries have had the greatest changes in Crop Yield and Soil Health Index, respectively, on a global level across the years 1990-2024.

For Extreme Weather Events, India had the highest level of Low Extreme Weather Events, Nigeria had the highest level of Medium, Argentina had the highest High, and the U.S. had the highest Very High. While these results do not measure change over time, they highlight which countries are experiencing the most extreme weather events at each level. For example, since the U.S. has the highest number of Very High events, it shows climate impacts are most severe in this country. This information provides a regional analysis of this variable, which can be used as a baseline for future change analysis.

c) Analysis 3

How do climate change factors correlate with crop yield?

For this question, we wanted to measure how well climate change factors (temperature, precipitation, CO2 emissions, and extreme weather events) correlated with crop yield. As the average temperature increases, does crop yield go down? Is there a lower crop yield when there are higher levels of extreme weather events? I also chose to include Soil Health Index in this analysis because it is a strong variable to include in the heatmap. We should expect crop yields to go up with higher soil health indices.

For this analysis, not much data wrangling/aggregation needed to be done. The important columns were filtered out from the original data and were correlated with each other to form the basis for the heatmap. The results were then visualized, with lighter colors indicating low levels of correlation and vibrant colors indicating high levels of correlation.

It is depicted that, aside from self-correlations, Crop Yield and Average Temperature show the highest correlation in the data. This relationship was visualized further using a scatterplot with the Average Temperature on the x-axis and Crop Yield on the y-axis.

This visualization makes it incredibly telling that the original dataset was synthesized for learning purposes; however, it still allows for meaningful analysis of the patterns. Between the ranges of -5 - 10 (°C), crop yield ranges from 0 - 3 (MT/HA). Between the ranges of 10 - 20 (°C), crop yield ranges from 2.5 - 5 (MT/HA). Between the ranges of 20 - 35 (°C), crop yield ranges from approx. 0.8 - 4 (MT/HA). This pattern indicates that the creator of the dataset wanted to highlight that higher crop yields occur at medium levels of temperature. This makes logical sense because if temperatures are at extremes (too high or too low), it is more difficult for crops to grow.

Because Extreme_Weather_Events is a binned variable, instead of using traditional correlation, I choose to measure the distribution of crop yields across categories of extreme weather events using boxplots. This allows us to determine which categories of extreme weather events have higher/lower median yields and the variability in yields. Given known facts about climate change, it is expected that categories with more extreme weather events show lower median crop yields and wider variability in yields, because some farms may be more resilient than others. Since it was determined in a previous question that the USA has the highest level of Very High extreme weather events, I was curious to see how this translated to this question. A similar plot depicting all countries was used for comparison.

One key finding was that crop yield is the highest when Average Temperature varies between 10 - 20 (°C). Although this is an effect of the synthesized nature of the data, it is still meaningful as a finding through the trends visualized.

d) Analysis 4

How do climate change and agricultural practices collectively influence economic impact from crop production globally?

Since this is a general question, we can divide it into two primary sub-questions. How does economic impact relate to crop yield? How does economic impact differ across countries and how does crop yield differ across adaptation strategies and extreme weather events? For example, we might expect that more developed countries have a greater economic impact, or certain adaptation strategies might yield a higher crop yield.

Beginning with the latter, barplots were used to measure these relationships. They can visually demonstrate the effects different categories have on economic impact. For each plot, the categorical variable is on the x-axis, and Economic_Impact_Million_USD or Crop_Yield_MT_per_HA is on the y-axis. To quantify the mean Economic_Impact_Million_USD for each category in each variable and the standard error bars (sem), each variable was grouped by the variable, and Economic_Impact_Million_USD was used to aggregate values by mean, standard deviation, and count. A function to calculate error was also used. The same was done for the graphs using Crop_Yield_MT_per_HA.

7) Recommendations to Stakeholders

As a reminder, the key stakeholders for this project include agricultural producers, policymakers, and environmental organizations. It is important to emphasize that the dataset used in this study is fully synthesized for educational purposes. Therefore, any recommendations derived from the analysis should not be interpreted as real-world guidance. Nonetheless, for the purposes of this project, recommendations will be formulated based on the patterns and trends identified in the data.

a) Recommendations 1

For Analysis 1, it was concluded that there is no significant relationship between Crop_Yield_MT_per_HA and Year, there are no patterns Average_Temperature_C, Total_Precipitation_mm, and CO2_Emissions_MT have with across the set of years, there has been increased activity in Very High levels of Extreme_Weather_Events in recent years, and there is are overall larger number of observations for soil samples that are functioning with limitations.

For agricultural producers, this indicates that steps need to be taken to improve soil health overall. The ratio between soil samples functioning with limitations and soil samples functioning without limitations is far too great, regardless of the year. Strengthening soil health practices may help control vulnerabilities in crop production long-term.

Since no clear trends were found between climate variables and yield over time, policymakers should invest in research to better understand the patterns of climate change. This study alone does not provide strong enough evidence of climate change, but more long-term and scientific datasets are needed to capture these patterns and inform effective policy. From the findings on soil health, policymakers should also prioritize funding for soil restoration and monitoring programs to improve long-term agricultural productivity.

For environmental organizations, it is recommended that they collaborate with researchers and policymakers to learn more about patterns of climate change and environmental practices. Environmental organizations can also translate the findings on soil health and extreme weather events into accessible educational materials to inform the public on how the environment has been progressing in recent years.

One important limitation of these recommendations is that they were measured with a relatively short time span (the years 1990-2024). To accurately measure climate change and conduct further analysis, it is recommended that stakeholders invest in research that collects data spanning back as far as possible. Another limitation is the limited variables used. This analysis does not include agricultural variables that may affect later aspects of the full study. Repeating the analysis using these variables over time may increase insights on actions that can be taken.

b) Recommendations 2

From Analysis 2, it was concluded that the most significant regions in the variables measured (changes in crop yield and soil health index, respectively) were Northeast Brazil and South Brazil. The primary countries appearing in the top 10 across both variables were Argentina, Brazil, and Russia. For Extreme Weather Events, India had the highest level of Low Extreme Weather Events, Nigeria had the highest level of Medium, Argentina had the highest High, and the U.S. had the highest Very High.

These conclusions help identify which countries and regions agricultural producers, policymakers, and environmental organizations should prioritize when allocating time and resources.

One recommendation for these stakeholders is targeting soil health interventions across Brazil, specifically Northeast and South Brazil. These were the two regions that saw the most change in crop yield and soil health index over the time period 1990-2024. Some examples of soil health interventions include soil restoration programs and sustainable farming initiatives. Additional support could also be provided to Argentina and Russia.

Another recommendation for these stakeholders is to tailor extreme weather prevention strategies to those who have experienced the highest levels of extreme weather events. Since India had the highest count of low levels of extreme weather events, it could maintain any resilience programs it has and invest more into other policies and programs. For the USA, however, it is recommended that they allocate more resources to programs that alleviate the risk of extreme weather. This could include emergency response tactics and more advanced forecasting systems.

One important limitation for this recommendation is that the overall change in crop yield and soil health index is measured by magnitude, not direction. A large numerical change does not necessarily reflect a severe problem. Changes could reflect natural variability, improved measurement, or positive developments rather than environmental degradation. While this was important for climate change, measuring direction in further study can show improvement or a shift to poor impacts.

c) Recommendations 3

From Analysis 3, it was concluded that crop yield is the highest when Average Temperature varies between 10 - 20 (°C). The analysis also showed that, in the USA, the median and range of crop yields associated with Very High levels of extreme weather events were slightly higher than those for the other event categories, a pattern not observed in the plot for all countries.

Based on these conclusions, it is recommended that agricultural producers prioritize growing crops in regions that are within the 10 - 20 (°C) temperature range. While these values may vary slightly depending on crop type, the data shows that for this dataset, it can be beneficial to use a 10 - 20 (°C) range to produce a higher crop yield. Furthermore, it is recommended that policymakers invest in these regions by providing technology, equipment, and agricultural resources to incentivize producers to grow in these areas.

Because the median crop yield in the USA associated with Very High extreme weather events was slightly higher than that of other countries, it is indicative that the USA may be implementing techniques or technology that make it more resilient to extreme weather and produce a higher crop yield. It is recommended that environmental organizations study the USA further to see how it takes on extreme weather and apply it to areas where crop yield is lower due to high levels of extreme weather. They can also provide information and resources to these other areas, including climate-resistant farming techniques and strong irrigation systems.

One limitation of this recommendation is that the identified 10–20°C optimal range is based on aggregated data across many crops. Individual crops have very different temperature requirements, so recommending producers shift production to this range may not be appropriate without crop-level analysis. Studies on different crop types and their preference towards certain temperatures may shift the insights in a different direction.

d) Recommendations 4

Analysis 4 concluded that there is no significant difference in economic impact between countries and crop yield across adaptation strategies. Furthermore, as crop yield increases, economic impact tends to increase as well.

For agricultural producers, these conclusions demonstrate that it may not be worth changing adaptation strategies to increase crop yield. Water management, crop rotation, no adaptation, organic farming, and drought-resistant crops do not differ in crop yield, so it is recommended that agricultural producers invest more time and money in moving to areas that fit in the recommended temperature range from Recommendation 3, for example.

For policymakers and environmental organizations, given that the data revealed no significant differences in economic impact across countries, it is recommended to prioritize strategies that strengthen climate adaptation and soil health globally, rather than assuming certain regions face uniquely severe challenges. This may include investing in research to identify effective techniques, equipment, and agricultural practices that enhance crop resilience to climate stressors. Furthermore, because the analysis showed that economic impact rises as crop yield increases, additional research could help uncover factors not captured in this study that further increase crop productivity.

One limitation of this recommendation is that adaptation strategies may not necessarily be comparable. For example, it may not be accurate to compare water management to crop rotation due to variation in scale, quality, and local conditions. Discussing this limitation with environmental scientists may be useful to accurately identify which adaptation strategies are best used for certain crop types. Another limitation of this recommendation is that economic impact may vary due to subsidies, labor costs, market access, and reporting practices. A deeper investigation into how this data was collected may impact results and their connection to crop yield.

8) Conclusion

When taken together, the four analyses reveal a complete picture of climate change, how it can have an impact on crops, and thus, an impact on the economy. Three primary variables that consistently demonstrated an effect on crop yield and/or economic impact throughout the study were temperature and extreme weather events. These variables were also compared both regionally and globally to identify the areas that require most immediate intervention.

When analyzing temperature, no strong patterns were observed at the global scale over time. However, at the regional level, variations between areas within each country became apparent, suggesting that temperature differences are more meaningfully interpreted geographically rather than temporally. For instance, Northeast Brazil experienced the greatest change in crop yield over time and also has the highest average temperature in the country of Brazil. While further research is needed to confirm the relationship between these observations, this example illustrates that regional changes within the given set of years can provide more significant insights than global changes within the same period. These conclusions highlight the need for stakeholders to target policies and programs toward regions where climate-dependent variables are most affected to drive meaningful change over time.

Although regional differences can provide detailed insights for changes over time, evaluating temperature and crop yield at the global level provided one of the most important findings of the study: crop yields are the highest between average temperatures of 10 - 20 (°C). When connected to the positive relationship between crop yield and average temperature, this finding suggests that prioritizing agricultural production in regions that fall between this temperature range could maximize yield and thus, economic impact. From the Figure 5, all of the regions contained within the dataset fall in this temperature range, and therefore, efforts to enhance agricultural productivity should focus on these areas.

Extreme_Weather_Events is another variable that demonstrated significant patterns across analysis questions. To begin, Very High levels of extreme weather events have experienced an increase in recent years. Then it was found that the USA has the highest count of Very High level of extreme weather events. Finally, the USA has a higher median of crop yield under the Very High level of the extreme weather events category compared to all countries globally. Together, this indicates that the USA may be employing effective strategies or innovations that help maintain crop productivity under severe weather conditions, and further study of these approaches could provide insights for other regions experiencing the increased activity of climate risk.

Overall, these analyses collectively point to the need for region-specific climate strategies and investments in agricultural systems that are optimized for ideal temperature ranges, improved resilience to extreme weather, and even enhanced soil health. These insights together guide stakeholders in promoting agricultural productivity and controlling the consequences of climate change.
